1. What do you mean by arrays give one example of array and how you can declared an array?
[04/11, 10:27] Saubhagya Bca: An array is a collection of similar data types stored in contiguous (continuous) memory locations.
It allows you to store multiple values in a single variable, instead of declaring separate variables for each value.
#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
    int numbers[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50}; // Declaration and initialization of array
    
    printf("The first element is: %d\n", numbers[0]);
    
    return 0;
}Output:

The first element is: 10
// Question-2. What do you mean by functions? Write the types of functions and give one example in code of each type.
// Function is a block of code used to perform a specific task.
// Types: 
// 1. Function with no arguments and no return value
// 2. Function with arguments and return value

void greet() { // No argument, no return
    printf("Hello! This is a simple function.\n");
}

int add(int a, int b) { // With arguments and return
    return a + b;
}

int main()
{
    greet(); // function call

    int result = add(10, 20);
    printf("Sum = %d\n", result);

    return 0;
}
[04/11, 10:04] kajal Bca: Question 3


#include<stdio.h>
int main()
{
    // Question-3. What do you mean by Pointers? Write a code how you can initialise the pointer.
    // A pointer is a variable that stores the memory address of another variable.

    int a = 10;
    int *ptr;   // pointer declaration
    ptr = &a;   // pointer initialization

    printf("Value of a: %d\n", a);
    printf("Address of a: %p\n", &a);
    printf("Value using pointer: %d\n", *ptr);

    return 0;
}
kajal bca: question 4


#include<stdio.h>
int main()
{
    // Question-4. What are the types of array? Write in a code 1D & 2D included.
    // Types of Array: 
    // 1. One Dimensional (1D)
    // 2. Two Dimensional (2D)

    // 1D Array
    int arr[5] = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
    printf("1D Array Elements:\n");
    for(int i=0; i<5; i++)
        printf("%d ", arr[i]);

    printf("\n\n");

    // 2D Array
    int mat[2][3] = { {1, 2, 3}, {4, 5, 6} };
    printf("2D Array Elements:\n");
    for(int i=0; i<2; i++) {
        for(int j=0; j<3; j++)
            printf("%d ", mat[i][j]);
        printf("\n");
    }

    return 0;
}
[04/11, 10:04] kajal Bca: QUESTION 5


#include<stdio.h>
int main()
{
    // Question-5. Explain the types of Operators in code.
    // Types: Arithmetic, Relational, Logical, Assignment, Increment/Decrement

    int a = 10, b = 5;

    // 1. Arithmetic Operators
    printf("Arithmetic: %d %d %d %d %d\n", a+b, a-b, a*b, a/b, a%b);

    // 2. Relational Operators
    printf("Relational: %d %d\n", a>b, a==b);

    // 3. Logical Operators
    printf("Logical: %d %d\n", (a>b && b>0), (a<b || b>0));

    // 4. Assignment Operator
    a += 5;
    printf("Assignment: %d\n", a);

    // 5. Increment/Decrement Operators
    a++; b--;
    printf("Inc/Dec: %d %d\n", a, b);

    return 0;
}
